[1] Dengue - Sonora, Mexico
Date: Tue, 19 Apr 2005 02:52:56 -0500
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source:El Imparcial [translated and edited]
<http://www.elimparcial.com/busqueda/home.aspx>

3 women contract dengue, says health secretary
----------------------------------------------
3 women living in the Cajeme and Etchojoa communities, who work at their
households, have been infected with the dengue virus in their own homes.
_Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes were found in the backyards of the homes of
these women. This vector is responsible for human-to-human transmission of
the dengue virus. One of the 3 women, who lives in Ciudad Obregon,
developed the hemorrhagic form of the disease after being stricken by the
infection for a 2nd time. Fortunately, she recovered. The 2 other women
also recovered uneventfully and only developed the so-called classic
symptoms, such as intense bone pain, eye pain, headache and joint pain,
sudden onset of fever, malaise, and a mild rash.
In addition to these 3 women, there are now 7 confirmed dengue cases in
Sonora this year [2005], 3 of them having had the hemorrhagic form of the
disease. Out of these 3 last cases, 2 recovered uneventfully, but one
person from the Cobachi community, La Colorada city council, died from the
disease.
Dengue, which is a disease that originated in Africa, appeared in Mexico in
1981. Since then, many people have acquired the infection, and there are
more and more complications for the population. However, as Health
Secretary Raymundo Lopez stated, it is not the mosquito itself that is the
causative agent of the epidemics, but the reluctance of the people of
Sonora to maintain clean backyards.
In the central, coastal and southern Sonora regions, the Health Secretariat
performed entomological studies, which have reported the presence of both
larvae and adult forms of _Aedes aegypti_.
Enforcement of rubbish elimination campaign:
There are also another 2 new dengue cases. The Health Secretariat declared
an alert for the Villa Bonita and Libertad communities, where the affected
women live. The 2 cases of hemorrhagic and classic dengue were detected in
the Villa Bonita and Libertad communities, and the health Secretariat
decreed an alert for these 2 places.
Mr Valente Parra-Dominguez, chief of Sanitary Authority No. 4, stated that,
as a result of the alert, no other positive case has been detected. One
woman affected in Villa Bonita is 35 years old, and the one from Libertad
is 58 years old. An urgent meeting with Mr. Felix Holguin, President of the
City Council, took place, and it was proposed to send a truck to the Health
Center in order to enforce rubbish elimination. Such actions have already
been taking place both in Libertad and in Villa Bonita, and they will
continue. He also stated that abate spraying and fumigation will be
performed in the communities where dengue has been detected, as well as in
places where there are suspected cases. Out of 37 suspected cases analyzed
until now, 3 cases have reported positive, the 1st one in Tobarito
precinct, an 11-year-old child. For the past 10 days, the results of tests
performed for 10 suspected cases revealed that 8 of them were negative for
dengue. Mr. Parra-Dominguez emphasized that the inspections to enforce
keeping clean backyards in every household will be continued.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[With warmer weather approaching the northern hemisphere, mosquitoborne
dengue infections are increasingly reported in endemic areas, such as
Sonora, Mexico. The campaign of eliminating the breeding grounds of the
arthropod vector _St. aegypti_ [formerly known as _Ae. aegypti_] by the
local authorities is both timely and effective. Other measures, such as
avoiding mosquito bites by wearing protective clothing and/or using insect
repellents during the cool hours of the day, such as the hours between dusk
and dawn when the mosquitoes are most active, should be taken. Public
education programs to increase public awareness should be imposed in Sonora
before and during the dengue season by local officials and schools. - Mod.RY]
